 <H1>Summary</H1> 
 <P><UL></P>

<P><LI><H2>Tree-structured indexes are ideal for range-searches, also good for equality searches.
</H2></P>

<P></UL><UL></P>

<P><LI><H2>ISAM is a static structure.
</H2></P>

<P><UL></P>

<P><LI>Only leaf pages modified; overflow pages needed.
<LI>Overflow chains can degrade performance unless size of data set and data distribution stay constant.
</UL></UL><UL></P>

<P><LI><H2>B+ tree is a dynamic structure.
</H2></P>

<P><UL></P>

<P><LI>Inserts/deletes leave tree height-balanced; log F N cost.
<LI>High fanout (F) means depth rarely more than 3 or 4.
<LI>Almost always better than maintaining a sorted file.</UL></UL></P>

